hist(diabetes$Pregnancies)

The data is right skewed with most of the patients having less than 5 pregnancies.

hist(diabetes$Age)

Most patients were between 20 to 30 years old with huge number of patients being between 20 to 25 years old.It suggests that most of the patients are adults

hist(diabetes$BloodPressure)

The histogram for the blood pressure is symmetric. Having too low or too high blood pressure is harmful for health.

The stepwise regression removed Skin thicknesss, Insulin, Blood Pressure and Pregnancies variables from the model. This model with variables removed has slightly lower AIC score (353.54) than the first order model (358.81), so this is the better model. The residual deviance is lower than the null deviance suggesting it’s a better model.

With the 95% of confidence the odds of having diabetes is:

  • 1.03 to 1.05 times higher for each 1 mg/dl increase in Glucose.

  • 1.016 to 1.13 times higher for 1 unit increase in BMI (body mass index).

  • 1.34 to 7.21 times higher for 1 unit increase in Diabetes Pedigree Function.

  • 1.007 to 1.087 times higher for 1 year increase in age.

Fit a model with interactions:

Next, we fit a full model with all two-way interactions.

diabetes$age.c = with (diabetes, Age - mean(Age))
m3 = glm (Outcome ~ (age.c +  Pregnancies + Glucose + BloodPressure + 
                       SkinThickness + Insulin+ BMI+
                       DiabetesPedigreeFunction)^2, family=binomial,
data=diabetes)

par (mfrow=c(1,1))
# Function to categorize a continuous variable into its quartiles
categorize = function (x) {
  quartiles = summary (x) [c(2, 3, 5)]
  result = rep ("Q1", length (x))
  result [(quartiles[1] < x) & (x <= quartiles [2])] = "Q2"
  result [(quartiles[2] < x) & (x <= quartiles [3])] = "Q3"
  result [quartiles[3] < x] = "Q4"
  return (result)
}
